## The two token layers (do not confuse them)

- **Scaffolding tokens** ‚Äî written as double curly braces in the templates; substituted once, at
  stamp time (slug `{{SLUG}}`, customer `{{CUSTOMER}}`, the four `*_SYSTEM` dialects, and dates as
  `____-__-__` fill-ins). None remain in the stamped files.
- **Authoring tokens** ‚Äî written as double angle brackets, `<<LIKE_THIS>>`; the business-value
  placeholders you fill **inside** the board and `roi-baseline.json` (`<<QTY_TOL_PCT>>`,
  `<<PRICE_TOL>>`, `<<OTIF_WINDOW>>`, `<<T_MANUAL_MIN>>`, `<<W_FTE>>`, ‚Ä¶). These are the editable
  surface ‚Äî leave them as tokens until you replace them with the customer's real numbers.

## The three source artifacts this kit unifies

1. **MCP connector kit** ‚Äî `frameworks/agents/retail-ops-mcp-kit` (referenced **by name**, not
   vendored). `connector-config.env.example` + `.mcp.json` wire its four servers to this
   customer's SaaS dialects. Run the servers from the kit; point your host at the stamped `.mcp.json`.
2. **Exception-spec DSL (item 4)** ‚Äî `exception-spec.inkspec.html` is copied **in full** (single-file,
   no build, no CDN, no network; all state in browser `localStorage`). Author the spec inside it,
   then export `policy.json` to `fixtures/retail_ops/`.
3. **ROI harness (item 5)** ‚Äî `roi-baseline.json` (cost deck) + `roi/ops_baseline.jsonl` /
   `roi/ops_automated.jsonl` + `roi/roi-report.inkspec.html`. Fill the decks with re-sourced
   customer numbers, then run the harness.

